Me and my dog -- Song -- The voice of God / by Mrs. Hemans -- Little girl's wish / by Charles Swain -- The cottage door / by M.M.M. -- Spring / by Mary Howitt -- The two ears of corn -- The moth -- Lines on a young lady weeping / by Miss Roberts -- Wandering Mary / by D. Carey -- Mottos for albums / by James Montgomery -- The step-mother -- On two infants, who died at the same time in the hooping cough -- The dying Negro / by the late Rev. J. Lawson of Calcutta -- Sister's love -- The first lamb -- Fly away, ladybird / by Mrs. S.C. Hall -- To a lady weeping over her departed child -- The grave of the pious cottager / by James Edmeston -- Invitation from a little to a very little lady -- For the album of a very little child -- The lily of the valley and the anemone -- My sister's garden -- On visiting the sylvan cottage of Mrs. H. More / by Anna Seward -- The bird's nest -- The cat and dog / by Mrs. S.C. Hall -- Affecting history of a wax doll -- The carrier pigeon -- A reflection on the loss of the Comet steam packet -- The butterfly and the two scorpions.

[cont.] Lines, addressed to a juvenile son, on presenting him with a watch as a New Year's present / by the Rev. Dr. Booker -- Transmigration, to a young lady, who said she "wished she was a flower" -- The dancing bear / by Miss Webb -- To Emma / by the Rev. John Horseman -- Forget me not -- Infant naturalists -- The youthful king, suggested by a picture of Edward the Sixth in his royal robes.
